The problem involves finding the limit of the probability of at least one match when a fair $n$-sided die is rolled $n$ independent times, with a match defined as side $i$ appearing on the $i$-th trial. The probability of at least one match is given by $P(\text{at least one match}) = 1 - P(\text{no matches})$.

Using the inclusion-exclusion principle, $P(\text{no matches})$ is expressed as:
\[
P(\text{no matches}) = \sum_{k=0}^{n} (-1)^k \binom{n}{k} \left(\frac{1}{n}\right)^k.
\]
As $n$ approaches infinity, this sum converges to $e^{-1}$, the reciprocal of the base of the natural logarithm. Therefore:
\[
\lim_{n \to \infty} P(\text{no matches}) = e^{-1} = \frac{1}{e}.
\]
Thus, the limit of the probability of at least one match is:
\[
\lim_{n \to \infty} P(\text{at least one match}) = 1 - \frac{1}{e}.
\]
Evaluating this expression numerically, $e \approx 2.718281828459$, so $\frac{1}{e} \approx 0.36787944117$. Then:
\[
1 - \frac{1}{e} \approx 1 - 0.36787944117 = 0.63212055883.
\]
Rounded to three significant figures, this is $0.632$.

The unit of the answer is dimensionless, as it is a probability.

Summary: The final answer is $0.632$
